SIMPLE: seat
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Seat
<hw>Seat</hw> <pr>(s⟦emac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>sete</ets>, Icel. <ets>saeti</ets>; akin to Sw.
<ets>s⟦aum⟧te</ets>, Dan. <ets>saede</ets>, MHG. <ets>s⟦amac⟧ze</ets>,
AS. <ets>set</ets>, <ets>setl</ets>, and E. <ets>sit</ets>. ⟦root⟧154.
See <er>Sit</er>, and cf. <er>Settle</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The place or thing upon which one sits; hence; anything
made to be sat in or upon, as a chair, bench, stool, saddle, or the
like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And Jesus . . . overthrew the tables of the money changers, and
the <qex>seats</qex> of them that sold doves.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. xxi.
12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The place occupied by anything, or where any person
or thing is situated, resides, or abides; a site; an abode, a station; a
post; a situation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where thou dwellest, even where Satan's <qex>seat</qex> is.</q>
<rj><qau>Rev. ii. 13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He that builds a fair house upon an ill <qex>seat</qex> committeth
himself to prison.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>seat</qex> of plenty, content, and tranquillity.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That part of a thing on which a person sits; <as>as,
the <ex>seat</ex> of a chair or saddle; the <ex>seat</ex> of a pair of
pantaloons</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A sitting; a right to sit; regular or appropriate
place of sitting; <as>as, a <ex>seat</ex> in a church; a <ex>seat</ex>
for the season in the opera house</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Posture, or way of sitting, on horseback.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She had so good a <qex>seat</qex> and hand she might be trusted
with any mount.</q> <rj><qau>G. Eliot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>A part or surface on which
another part or surface rests; <as>as, a valve
<ex>seat</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Seat worm</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the
pinworm.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seat</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Seat
<hw>Seat</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Seated</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Seating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To place on a seat;
to cause to sit down; <as>as, to <ex>seat</ex> one's
self</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The guests were no sooner <qex>seated</qex> but they entered into
a warm debate.</q> <rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause to occupy a post, site, situation, or the
like; to station; to establish; to fix; to settle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus high . . . is King Richard <qex>seated</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They had <qex>seated</qex> themselves in New Guiana.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Raleigh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To assign a seat to, or the seats of; to give a
sitting to; <as>as, to <ex>seat</ex> a church, or persons in a
church</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To fix; to set firm.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From their foundations, loosening to and fro,⟦br⟧
They plucked the <qex>seated</qex> hills.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To settle; to plant with inhabitants; as to
<xex>seat</xex> a country.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>W.
Stith.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To put a seat or bottom in; <as>as, to <ex>seat</ex>
a chair</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seat</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Seat
<hw>Seat</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To rest; to lie down.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sea tang</ent>⟦br⟧
